<section class="section section--alt" id="guide-cleanup-vs-monthly-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Cleanup versus monthly, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Both services categorize transactions, reconcile accounts, and produce reliable numbers &mdash; which is exactly why they get conflated. The difference isn&rsquo;t the work; it&rsquo;s <em>what state your file is in</em> and <em>what shape the engagement takes</em>. <strong>Cleanup</strong> (sometimes called catch-up) is a one-time project for a file that&rsquo;s behind, disorganized, or no longer trustworthy. It has a defined scope, a written estimate, and a finish line: when the books are accurate and reconciled, the cleanup is done.</p>
      <p><strong>Monthly bookkeeping</strong> is an ongoing service for a file that&rsquo;s already accurate. Each month, transactions get categorized, accounts get reconciled, and the period gets closed &mdash; so the numbers stay current and the file never drifts back into a cleanup situation. The two relate in a fixed order: when a file is behind, cleanup comes first to establish a clean baseline, then monthly bookkeeping maintains that baseline going forward. Trying to maintain a file you don&rsquo;t trust just carries the errors forward, which is why a reputable firm scopes cleanup first when the books are behind. This page is the decision guide &mdash; the cleanup and monthly service pages, linked below, cover each engagement in full.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

